PNEUMONIA, CAUSE UNKNOWN - SOUTH KOREA (02): (SEOUL), VETERINARY STUDENTS
*************************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

[1]
Date: Wed 28 Oct 2015
Source: Korean Ministry of Health [in Korean, trans. by Korean volunteers, edited]
http://www.mw.go.kr/front_new/al/sal0301vw.jsp?PAR_MENU_ID=04&MENU_ID=0403&page=1&CONT_SEQ=327049


Epidemiological studies are being conducted for an unknown disease with pneumonia-like symptoms [that] occurred at Konkuk University.

The Korean Center for Disease Control & Prevention [KCDC] (director, Yang Byung Guk) said the central epidemiology investigation team was dispatched (on 28 Oct 15) in order to conduct epidemiology studies in Konkuk University, because after 19 Oct 15, unknown-cause pneumonia patients (3 cases) from Konkuk University Animal Life Sciences Building were reported in Gwangjin-gu Health Center.

KCDC confirmed the unknown-cause pneumonia on the day of (27 Oct 15); the result of the initial epidemiological test from the health center was reported and the central epidemiology investigation team was dispatched to proceed with epidemiology studies in detail; as of 27 Oct 15 evening, 10 more patients were recorded.

As of today (28 Oct 15), according to the central epidemiology investigation team, they confirmed that patients are concentrically from 3 laboratories inside the building, so they will focus on finding co-exposure factors.

From 19-28 Oct 2015, 21 patients showed symptoms such as pneumonia, respiratory symptoms, and fever, and they will receive treatment in the National Inpatient Hospital until the pathogen is confirmed.

Konkuk University will continue the building shutdown until the cause is identified and safety is assured.

KCDC is conducting preventative measures, such as indoor disinfection, in consultation with the university and will obtain a list of building users in order to strengthen monitoring. In addition, they will conduct detailed epidemiological investigations.

--
