******
[2]
Date: Thu 29 Oct 2015
Source: Korean Ministry of Health [in Korean, trans. by Korean volunteers, edited]
http://www.mw.go.kr/front_new/al/sal0301vw.jsp?PAR_MENU_ID=04&MENU_ID=0403&page=1&CONT_SEQ=327080


As of 29 Oct 2015 0:00 KST, the Korea Centers for Disease Control & Prevention (director, Yang Byung Guk) investigated a total of 31 unknown-cause respiratory disease cases in relation to Konkuk University, which are 10 more cases than the previous day's numbers.

31 patients reported fever and respiratory symptoms, of which 23 patients are receiving treatment from the National Inpatient Hospital, and 8 of them who have relatively minor symptoms are quarantined at home.

According to the epidemiology investigation team, all 31 cases of unknown cause respiratory disease are from the Animal Life Science building, and the outbreak occurred intensively over the past week, which indicates that the situation occurred by common factors associated with the building.

In order to identify the cause, the KCDC proceeded with bacterial and viral testing by collecting patient and environmental samples from the building. Unusual findings have not been confirmed until now.

Test results:
- For the cause, genetic testing and serum antibody tests were conducted on some patients, which were confirmed negative.
- PCR test result negative infectious disease
- respiratory bacteria: mycoplasma, chlamydia, whooping cough, diphtheria
- respiratory viruses: Merck's, adenovirus, RS virus, parainfluenza virus, virus meth pneumophila, Boca virus, influenza virus, coronavirus
- PCR negative [for?] infectious diseases in antibody test progress
Brucellosis, Q fever, Legionella (3 weeks after retesting with convalescent serum)
*Although test came out negative, it is not excluded from the cause of infection, and retest will be conducted according to symptoms.
- Chemical materials and environmental factors, as well as a mass outbreak by infectious pathogens will be investigated from various angles.

Meanwhile, Konkuk University Animal Life Science building was closed down on 28 Oct 2015. People who visited the building from 8-28 Oct 2015 and have fever are encourged to report to the KCDC Call Center (109).
Also, the SK Group held an employment exam at the building on 25 Oct 2015. The SK group instructed 500 applicants to report to the KCDC Call Center (109) if they have unusual symptoms.
- In addition, the KCDC asked the Korean Medical Association and Korean Hospital Association for cooperation to check patients with fever and respiratory symptoms [if] they have ever visited Konkuk University Animal Life Sciences building.

--
