******
[3]
Date: Fri 30 Oct 2015
Source: [in Korean, trans. by Korean volunteers, edited]
http://www.mw.go.kr/front_new/al/sal0301vw.jsp?PAR_MENU_ID=04&MENU_ID=0403&page=1&CONT_SEQ=327095


Report on the 2nd day respiratory disease investigation arising from Konkuk University
------------------------------
The Korea Centers for Disease Control & Prevention (director, Yang Byung Guk) said specific findings were not found from the result of the human samples test (conducted until 29 Oct 15) for 16 species of bacterial and viral pathogens in relation to Konkuk University's respiratory disease outbreak.

One patient was confirmed to be positive for rhinovirus, which is one of the common cold viruses from genetic testing, but it is not common in [to? - Mod.SH] all patients [and] is thought to be irrelevant to the respiratory disease.

In addition, there are no patients confirmed positive for serum antibody test (brucellosis, Q fever, legionella), which shall be reaffirmed through secondary inspection (convalescent serology) after 3 weeks.

In order to research bacterial and viral, as well as environmental and chemical factors, experts from various fields, including infectious diseases and toxicology, will cooperate with an epidemiology investigation team, and the causes of the respiratory disease will be identified through a comprehensive review.

As of 30 Oct 2015 0 PM KST, a total of 45 cases are currently being investigated, and there are confirmed pneumonia radiological patterns in 34 cases who are identified as the suspected patients. They are distributed in 7 hospitals under quarantine and receiving treatment, and they show fever, muscle pain, and mild pneumonia symptoms, but there are no severe cases among 34 so far.

For 11 of them who are currently staying at home, it will be determined whether or not they should be identified as suspected patients and hospitalized after they undergo chest radiography.

*Suspected Patients: people who visited Konkuk University Animal Life Sciences Building after 8 Oct 2015 with fever of 37.5 C [99 F] and a chest radiological pneumonia pattern.

Management system for the building entrance:
- A liaison system was operated for Konkuk University Animal Life Sciences Building faculty, and entrants who have symptoms such as fever are to be reported voluntarily.
- Starting this afternoon (30 Oct 15), the KCDC Call Center (109) will carry out a monitoring system to check on individuals who have symptoms twice a day.
- However, for 500 people who take the SK Group employment exam on 25 Oct 15, a personal precaution guide will be given as a one-time exposure. A system for voluntary reporting (109 call center) for adverse symptoms will be in place.
- Konkuk University Animal Life Science Building (7-story building) is maintaining a state of disinfection and completely controlling access as preventative measures.
- According to the epidemiology investigation team, the suspected cases have been confirmed to have occurred intensively on the 5th floor laboratory.
- The building workers, entrants, laboratory workers, and the workers near the laboratory will be classified and examined in detail.
- KCDC are investigating and taking necessary steps to find the cause and manage the respiratory disease.
- KCDC will actively cooperate with relevant ministries and academic-medical specialists, and will plan to inform the public and the media often.

--
